Okay, so now the news
the last few days,

00:06:08.802 --> 00:06:10.537 align:middle line:90%
it started last Friday.

00:06:10.537 --> 00:06:15.642 align:middle line:84%
Apparently I remember reading
in one article that 500...

00:06:15.642 --> 00:06:21.448 align:middle line:84%
500 tons of gold were dumped
in one day onto the market.

00:06:21.448 --> 00:06:24.618 align:middle line:84%
We're seeing very unusual
patterns in the gold market.

00:06:24.618 --> 00:06:30.257 align:middle line:84%
Gold has been in a
consolidation since late 2011.

00:06:30.257 --> 00:06:32.926 align:middle line:84%
We... To give you an
example, gold started

00:06:32.926 --> 00:06:35.729 align:middle line:84%
up in a very significant
way about 12 years ago.

00:06:35.729 --> 00:06:38.031 align:middle line:90%
So for the last 12 years,

00:06:38.031 --> 00:06:41.602 align:middle line:84%
gold has out performed the
Dow every year for 12 years

00:06:41.602 --> 00:06:44.571 align:middle line:84%
where that's a stunning
bull market,

00:06:44.571 --> 00:06:48.609 align:middle line:84%
and we saw gold hit a
high in September, 2011,

00:06:48.609 --> 00:06:51.144 align:middle line:84%
and it's been consolidating
since,

00:06:51.144 --> 00:06:54.648 align:middle line:84%
and what's interesting
is the primary move

00:06:54.648 --> 00:06:57.651 align:middle line:84%
up in gold has very
much tracked two things.

00:06:57.651 --> 00:07:00.654 align:middle line:84%
One is the increase
in treasury debt

00:07:00.654 --> 00:07:02.656 align:middle line:84%
and sovereign government
debt worldwide.

00:07:02.656 --> 00:07:06.827 align:middle line:84%
So the more we print, you know,
and gold is not so much going

00:07:06.827 --> 00:07:10.931 align:middle line:84%
up in value as the fiat
currency is going down in value.

00:07:10.931 --> 00:07:13.000 align:middle line:84%
So that's what we
call debasement.

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:16.336 align:middle line:84%
So but we've also seen
is for the last, say,

00:07:16.336 --> 00:07:18.972 align:middle line:84%
5 years a very tight
relationship...

00:07:18.972 --> 00:07:23.076 align:middle line:84%
If you do a correlation of the
copper price with the S&P 500,

00:07:23.076 --> 00:07:24.645 align:middle line:84%
you get a very tight
correlation.

00:07:24.645 --> 00:07:29.583 align:middle line:84%
So we've seen the
Federal Reserve does a

00:07:29.583 --> 00:07:30.417 align:middle line:90%
quantitative ease.

00:07:30.417 --> 00:07:31.652 align:middle line:90%
It's called quantitative ease,

00:07:31.652 --> 00:07:34.187 align:middle line:84%
and so they spend the money
supply, and commodities

00:07:34.187 --> 00:07:35.389 align:middle line:90%
and stocks go up together.

00:07:35.389 --> 00:07:39.092 align:middle line:84%
So risk-based assets, real
things, go up together.

00:07:39.092 --> 00:07:43.130 align:middle line:84%
What suddenly started last
year is a tremendous divergence

00:07:43.130 --> 00:07:47.200 align:middle line:84%
between commodities and the
stock market and you see it.

00:07:47.200 --> 00:07:50.404 align:middle line:84%
If it's quite extraordinary,
divergence of the copper price

00:07:50.404 --> 00:07:52.606 align:middle line:84%
and stocks, and you're
watching it,

00:07:52.606 --> 00:07:54.675 align:middle line:84%
and you're thinking
how can this be?

00:07:54.675 --> 00:07:56.642 align:middle line:90%
What is going on?

00:07:56.642 --> 00:07:59.279 align:middle line:84%
Now the market people
would argue

00:07:59.279 --> 00:08:02.916 align:middle line:84%
that we're experiencing
tremendous deflation globally.

00:08:02.916 --> 00:08:06.787 align:middle line:84%
The economy's slowing down,
and that's very deflationary.

00:08:06.787 --> 00:08:10.223 align:middle line:84%
You know, the people who argue
that the system is managed say,

00:08:10.223 --> 00:08:14.328 align:middle line:84%
you know, "This can't
occur naturally."

00:08:14.328 --> 00:08:17.664 align:middle line:84%
And, in fact, you
have reasons to want

00:08:17.664 --> 00:08:20.901 align:middle line:84%
to bring commodity prices down,
and you have reasons to want

00:08:20.901 --> 00:08:22.536 align:middle line:84%
to bring the precious
metals prices

00:08:22.536 --> 00:08:26.406 align:middle line:84%
down that are very powerful
from a management standpoint,

00:08:26.406 --> 00:08:28.976 align:middle line:84%
and when we saw, we saw
a very powerful drop,

00:08:28.976 --> 00:08:30.877 align:middle line:84%
we had one of the big
Wall Street firms come

00:08:30.877 --> 00:08:33.847 align:middle line:84%
out on Wednesday and say,
"Oh, gold's going down.

00:08:33.847 --> 00:08:37.284 align:middle line:84%
We recommend to all of
our clients to short it."

00:08:37.284 --> 00:08:38.484 align:middle line:90%
And then you...

00:08:38.484 --> 00:08:42.022 align:middle line:84%
it was stable for a day,
and then Friday, nosedive.

00:08:42.022 --> 00:08:46.860 align:middle line:84%
Right. Monday, more nosedive,
and then after the nosedive

00:08:46.860 --> 00:08:50.264 align:middle line:84%
on Monday, you see the
CME come out and say, "Oh,

00:08:50.264 --> 00:08:53.467 align:middle line:84%
we're increasing margin
requirements on gold, silver."

00:08:53.467 --> 00:08:56.136 align:middle line:84%
Margin requirements is one of
the things that gets increased,

00:08:56.136 --> 00:08:58.605 align:middle line:84%
and, you know, you pull
up the margin requirements

00:08:58.605 --> 00:09:00.607 align:middle line:90%
and the market price drops.

00:09:00.607 --> 00:09:01.742 align:middle line:90%
So there's a...

00:09:01.742 --> 00:09:05.379 align:middle line:84%
you know, there's
several powerful arguments

00:09:05.379 --> 00:09:09.516 align:middle line:84%
as to why institutionally
the people

00:09:09.516 --> 00:09:11.852 align:middle line:84%
who manage the financial
system and are concerned

00:09:11.852 --> 00:09:14.521 align:middle line:84%
with financial stability
could want gold to come down.

00:09:14.521 --> 00:09:17.924 align:middle line:84%
Is there a gold cartel
so to speak?

00:09:17.924 --> 00:09:23.530 align:middle line:84%
Well, if you look at who has
traditionally managed this

00:09:23.530 --> 00:09:26.900 align:middle line:84%
market, the bullion banks in
London and the United States,

00:09:26.900 --> 00:09:29.369 align:middle line:84%
and that says, "Yes,
there's a gold cartel,"

00:09:29.369 --> 00:09:30.937 align:middle line:90%
but in my personal experience,

00:09:30.937 --> 00:09:36.309 align:middle line:84%
gold is probably the most
important asset globally

00:09:36.309 --> 00:09:39.680 align:middle line:84%
that behind the scenes
is used to balance trade.

00:09:39.680 --> 00:09:42.849 align:middle line:84%
You know, gold is the power
within the financial community,

00:09:42.849 --> 00:09:46.953 align:middle line:84%
gold is one of the
major power positions.

00:09:46.953 --> 00:09:50.991 align:middle line:84%
So I don't care what
the price is, you know,

00:09:50.991 --> 00:09:54.561 align:middle line:84%
who's got the gold is
a very important part.

00:09:54.561 --> 00:09:57.764 align:middle line:84%
Well, yes, and what seemed to
me to be happening, and, again,

00:09:57.764 --> 00:10:02.402 align:middle line:84%
I'm just an amateur spectator,
but what seemed to me is

00:10:02.402 --> 00:10:05.172 align:middle line:84%
that this was also
an interesting way

00:10:05.172 --> 00:10:08.208 align:middle line:84%
as the stakes rise
globally and it becomes...

