Now if you're trying to finance
we now have the Federal Reserve

00:12:37.090 --> 00:12:39.860 align:middle line:90%
buying over 90% of the auctions.

00:12:39.860 --> 00:12:45.098 align:middle line:84%
Right. Okay, so if you're
responsible to borrow the money,

00:12:45.098 --> 00:12:47.234 align:middle line:84%
you need to finance
Social Security

00:12:47.234 --> 00:12:49.369 align:middle line:84%
to finance disability
to finance welfare.

00:12:49.369 --> 00:12:52.772 align:middle line:84%
Right. To finance all
those defense contracts,

00:12:52.772 --> 00:12:57.010 align:middle line:84%
and the treasury market
is dropping that fast.

00:12:57.010 --> 00:12:58.078 align:middle line:90%
You know, you're going

00:12:58.078 --> 00:12:59.846 align:middle line:84%
from something that's
relatively stable

00:12:59.846 --> 00:13:03.516 align:middle line:84%
to something that's experiencing
relatively swift drops.

00:13:03.516 --> 00:13:05.252 align:middle line:90%
That's a real...

00:13:05.252 --> 00:13:10.423 align:middle line:84%
So you have to create something
to shift the relative value.

00:13:10.423 --> 00:13:12.092 align:middle line:84%
Well, you have to
defend the bond market,

00:13:12.092 --> 00:13:15.428 align:middle line:84%
and the interesting thing is
to defend the bond market,

00:13:15.428 --> 00:13:17.264 align:middle line:84%
you've got to defend
the stock market.

00:13:17.264 --> 00:13:18.665 align:middle line:90%
Right. Okay?

00:13:18.665 --> 00:13:22.002 align:middle line:84%
And you've got to find a managed
process for these things to...

00:13:22.002 --> 00:13:25.538 align:middle line:84%
you know, for these
shifts to happen,

00:13:25.538 --> 00:13:27.941 align:middle line:84%
and the problem is precious
metals is a little bit

00:13:27.941 --> 00:13:29.709 align:middle line:90%
like the smoke alarm.

00:13:29.709 --> 00:13:32.412 align:middle line:84%
You know, the price
moves up too fast,

00:13:32.412 --> 00:13:34.948 align:middle line:84%
and then suddenly
everybody's looking.

00:13:34.948 --> 00:13:36.316 align:middle line:90%
Right... at what's going on.

00:13:36.316 --> 00:13:39.085 align:middle line:84%
Right. You've got a
spiral, a danger, a spiral,

00:13:39.085 --> 00:13:42.923 align:middle line:84%
or a contagion happening
that can be very dangerous.

00:13:42.923 --> 00:13:44.023 align:middle line:90%
But what about in reverse

00:13:44.023 --> 00:13:46.993 align:middle line:84%
like what happened
last Friday and Monday?

00:13:46.993 --> 00:13:48.295 align:middle line:84%
Well here's the interesting
thing

00:13:48.295 --> 00:13:50.964 align:middle line:84%
because we don't know what
happened or why it happened

00:13:50.964 --> 00:13:53.400 align:middle line:84%
and how much was markets
versus management,

00:13:53.400 --> 00:13:58.071 align:middle line:84%
but let me just postulate
some possible scenarios.

00:13:58.071 --> 00:14:04.611 align:middle line:84%
We know we've had quite a sort
of alarm bell ring globally

00:14:04.611 --> 00:14:06.846 align:middle line:84%
as a result of what
happened in Cyprus.

00:14:06.846 --> 00:14:08.515 align:middle line:84%
We'll talk about that
in some detail, yeah.

00:14:08.515 --> 00:14:13.253 align:middle line:84%
Right. So the first, you
know, for my entire lifetime,

00:14:13.253 --> 00:14:16.890 align:middle line:84%
we have most people in the
developed world saying, "Oh,

00:14:16.890 --> 00:14:19.659 align:middle line:84%
I don't have to worry that we're
running the economy in a way

00:14:19.659 --> 00:14:22.629 align:middle line:84%
that doesn't make sense because
I have a government guarantee.

00:14:22.629 --> 00:14:23.763 align:middle line:90%
I have a treasury bond.

00:14:23.763 --> 00:14:25.198 align:middle line:90%
I have an insured deposit.

00:14:25.198 --> 00:14:25.999 align:middle line:90%
I don't have to worry.

00:14:25.999 --> 00:14:27.067 align:middle line:90%
You know, my deck chair

00:14:27.067 --> 00:14:29.002 align:middle line:84%
on the Titanic is
government-guaranteed,

00:14:29.002 --> 00:14:31.471 align:middle line:84%
so I don't have to worry
about, you know, the boat,

00:14:31.471 --> 00:14:33.039 align:middle line:84%
because the boat's
big and safe, right?

00:14:33.039 --> 00:14:34.174 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, right.

00:14:34.174 --> 00:14:36.443 align:middle line:84%
So we've all been living
in this sort of bubble

00:14:36.443 --> 00:14:37.777 align:middle line:90%
where we don't have to worry

00:14:37.777 --> 00:14:40.113 align:middle line:84%
about whether things
are fundamentally sound.

00:14:40.113 --> 00:14:41.948 align:middle line:84%
That's part of the problem
with being in a debt

00:14:41.948 --> 00:14:43.783 align:middle line:84%
versus an equity model
and why I think going

00:14:43.783 --> 00:14:45.251 align:middle line:84%
in an equity model
is very healthy,

00:14:45.251 --> 00:14:50.657 align:middle line:84%
but so what happened was the
first IMF and ECB proposal

00:14:50.657 --> 00:14:54.160 align:middle line:84%
for the resolution of the
banking problems in Cyprus was

00:14:54.160 --> 00:14:59.532 align:middle line:84%
to tax the insured deposits,
and even when they backed off,

00:14:59.532 --> 00:15:00.600 align:middle line:90%
there was a huge uproar.

00:15:00.600 --> 00:15:02.669 align:middle line:84%
Even when they backed
off, you know,

00:15:02.669 --> 00:15:06.039 align:middle line:84%
capital controls were placed
on it, which said if you're

00:15:06.039 --> 00:15:08.775 align:middle line:84%
in a weaker bank or a
weaker country, you know,

00:15:08.775 --> 00:15:10.810 align:middle line:84%
your euro insurance
is not so good

00:15:10.810 --> 00:15:12.512 align:middle line:84%
as the euro insurance
in Germany.

00:15:12.512 --> 00:15:14.581 align:middle line:84%
You know, now you're
talking about a 2-tiered,

00:15:14.581 --> 00:15:16.449 align:middle line:90%
and that was a wakeup call

00:15:16.449 --> 00:15:18.985 align:middle line:84%
because that was the first time
really in the developed world

00:15:18.985 --> 00:15:22.155 align:middle line:84%
that somebody said,
you know, "Yeah,

00:15:22.155 --> 00:15:23.990 align:middle line:84%
maybe you have insurance,
maybe you don't."

00:15:23.990 --> 00:15:25.992 align:middle line:84%
Right. You know, so
immediately everybody

00:15:25.992 --> 00:15:29.963 align:middle line:84%
in the United States is
saying, "Well, what about FDIC?"

00:15:29.963 --> 00:15:34.200 align:middle line:84%
Now, what had been happening
was we went through the process

00:15:34.200 --> 00:15:39.239 align:middle line:84%
in the 2008-2009 where we
bailed out banks, and of course,

00:15:39.239 --> 00:15:41.775 align:middle line:84%
Europe has been going
through a situation

00:15:41.775 --> 00:15:44.110 align:middle line:84%
where literally what we did
is we took the debt that was

00:15:44.110 --> 00:15:47.814 align:middle line:84%
on the banks and we moved
it to the government.

00:15:47.814 --> 00:15:50.383 align:middle line:84%
You know, so government
bailed out the debt,

00:15:50.383 --> 00:15:55.622 align:middle line:84%
and the banks got protected at
the cost of the greater system,

00:15:55.622 --> 00:16:01.061 align:middle line:84%
and when we passed Dot
Frank after the bailouts,

00:16:01.061 --> 00:16:03.930 align:middle line:84%
we passed a law, Dot
Frank, and said, okay,

00:16:03.930 --> 00:16:06.800 align:middle line:84%
the regulators can't do
too big to fail anymore.

00:16:06.800 --> 00:16:10.537 align:middle line:84%
They've got to come up with
resolution methods that allow us

00:16:10.537 --> 00:16:14.140 align:middle line:84%
to take down a bank,
strip a bank apart,

00:16:14.140 --> 00:16:18.545 align:middle line:84%
resolve a troubled bank without
guaranteeing all their deposit

00:16:18.545 --> 00:16:20.447 align:middle line:84%
and allowing them to
keep behaving this way.

00:16:20.447 --> 00:16:24.250 align:middle line:84%
We need big banks to
fail, and we absolutely do

00:16:24.250 --> 00:16:27.454 align:middle line:84%
because we have created
a financial sector,

00:16:27.454 --> 00:16:30.323 align:middle line:84%
which is far bigger
than what we need,

00:16:30.323 --> 00:16:32.325 align:middle line:90%
and it's become like a tapeworm.

00:16:32.325 --> 00:16:33.726 align:middle line:90%
Right. Right.

00:16:33.726 --> 00:16:37.564 align:middle line:84%
Right. So you say we need
the large banks to fail.

00:16:37.564 --> 00:16:42.068 align:middle line:84%
We need a way to shrink this
industry back to a level

00:16:42.068 --> 00:16:44.704 align:middle line:84%
which supports fundamental
economics

00:16:44.704 --> 00:16:46.706 align:middle line:90%
as opposed to as a parasite.

00:16:46.706 --> 00:16:50.510 align:middle line:84%
So, you know, so we need
to shrink the sector.

00:16:50.510 --> 00:16:51.778 align:middle line:90%
How do we do it?

00:16:51.778 --> 00:16:55.782 align:middle line:84%
So the regulators were
required by Dot Frank to go out

00:16:55.782 --> 00:16:57.317 align:middle line:84%
and figure out how they
were going to do this

00:16:57.317 --> 00:16:59.185 align:middle line:84%
and get this ready,
and, in fact,

00:16:59.185 --> 00:17:03.322 align:middle line:84%
we've seen publications both
in Europe and North America

00:17:03.322 --> 00:17:06.626 align:middle line:84%
with regulations saying, okay,
here's how we're going to do it,

00:17:06.626 --> 00:17:09.162 align:middle line:84%
and, of course, what it means is
the uninsured deposits are going

00:17:09.162 --> 00:17:10.763 align:middle line:84%
to get written off,
the creditors are going

00:17:10.763 --> 00:17:12.932 align:middle line:84%
to get written off or
swapped for equity,

00:17:12.932 --> 00:17:18.404 align:middle line:84%
and so the world is now looking
at this and realizing, oh,

00:17:18.404 --> 00:17:22.274 align:middle line:84%
you know, accountability as we
can, you know, is on its way.

00:17:22.274 --> 00:17:24.944 align:middle line:84%
Now, if you are in
an environment

00:17:24.944 --> 00:17:29.716 align:middle line:84%
where you're a regulator and
you have to resolve a large bank

00:17:29.716 --> 00:17:34.654 align:middle line:84%
in this way, one of the dangers
is if the gold price is high

00:17:34.654 --> 00:17:40.527 align:middle line:84%
and it sends an alarm bell like
Cyprus did where everybody said,

00:17:40.527 --> 00:17:42.729 align:middle line:84%
you know, everybody who
had gold in Cyprus was

00:17:42.729 --> 00:17:44.898 align:middle line:84%
in much better shape than
everybody who had, you know,

00:17:44.898 --> 00:17:46.166 align:middle line:90%
insured bank deposits.

00:17:46.166 --> 00:17:51.671 align:middle line:84%
Right. So if you're a regulator,
you have reason to want

00:17:51.671 --> 00:17:54.140 align:middle line:84%
to get a reset in
the gold price.

00:17:54.140 --> 00:17:58.378 align:middle line:84%
Because that will help reset the
value of the dollar, etc. Well,

00:17:58.378 --> 00:18:03.249 align:middle line:84%
because let's say your gold high
has been approximately 1900.

00:18:03.249 --> 00:18:06.052 align:middle line:84%
Now you're a little
bit below 1400.

00:18:06.052 --> 00:18:09.589 align:middle line:84%
You reset it down to 1400,
then you resolve the bank even

00:18:09.589 --> 00:18:12.759 align:middle line:84%
if it kicks it back up to
1800, you know, you're still

00:18:12.759 --> 00:18:17.263 align:middle line:84%
within the zone, and my guess,
and this is just a guess,

00:18:17.263 --> 00:18:21.100 align:middle line:84%
is that it is in the interest
of the financial system

00:18:21.100 --> 00:18:24.137 align:middle line:84%
to have a managed rise
in the gold price,

00:18:24.137 --> 00:18:27.507 align:middle line:84%
but to have a managed
rise and to do it in a way

00:18:27.507 --> 00:18:33.246 align:middle line:84%
that doesn't trigger this
contagion throughout the bond

00:18:33.246 --> 00:18:35.915 align:middle line:84%
market because the bond
market is the big intimidator.

00:18:35.915 --> 00:18:39.886 align:middle line:84%
Right. But yet at the same
time while this was going on,

00:18:39.886 --> 00:18:42.455 align:middle line:84%
I was reading, you know,
various articles on it,

00:18:42.455 --> 00:18:44.123 align:middle line:84%
and one of the articles
was saying remember,

00:18:44.123 --> 00:18:46.059 align:middle line:90%
this is a paper market.

00:18:46.059 --> 00:18:47.460 align:middle line:90%
This is a paper market.

00:18:47.460 --> 00:18:51.798 align:middle line:84%
It's not the real asset physical
gold, and then at the same time,

00:18:51.798 --> 00:18:55.235 align:middle line:84%
the price of paper gold
was dropping like a stone,

00:18:55.235 --> 00:19:00.073 align:middle line:84%
the buy-to-sell ratio in the
physical market was 50 to 1.

00:19:00.073 --> 00:19:03.076 align:middle line:90%
There have been, you know,

00:19:03.076 --> 00:19:06.613 align:middle line:84%
if you look at the physical
market both institutional

00:19:06.613 --> 00:19:10.516 align:middle line:84%
and retail, there have
been very unusual patterns.

00:19:10.516 --> 00:19:11.718 align:middle line:90%
So in the retail markets here

00:19:11.718 --> 00:19:15.722 align:middle line:84%
in the United States we've
seen tremendous reports

00:19:15.722 --> 00:19:17.523 align:middle line:84%
at retail level from
the dealers.

00:19:17.523 --> 00:19:18.458 align:middle line:90%
They can't get product.

00:19:18.458 --> 00:19:19.826 align:middle line:90%
They can't...

00:19:19.826 --> 00:19:22.362 align:middle line:84%
Right. You know, 90% silver,
they can't get it at any price.

00:19:22.362 --> 00:19:28.001 align:middle line:84%
We saw the premiums on 90%
go from 2 to 3% to, you know,

00:19:28.001 --> 00:19:31.204 align:middle line:84%
12% to clear and then you
couldn't clear it at any price,

00:19:31.204 --> 00:19:32.739 align:middle line:90%
which is very unusual.

00:19:32.739 --> 00:19:36.976 align:middle line:84%
So that would indicate that
it's the paper price coming down

00:19:36.976 --> 00:19:39.846 align:middle line:84%
and the physical market
can't clear the paper price.

00:19:39.846 --> 00:19:43.082 align:middle line:84%
Now I've had reports from
both the institutional...

00:19:43.082 --> 00:19:45.852 align:middle line:84%
you see reports from the
institutional markets

00:19:45.852 --> 00:19:48.087 align:middle line:90%
that there's serious problems

00:19:48.087 --> 00:19:51.658 align:middle line:84%
in the physical market
or seizes up .

00:19:51.658 --> 00:19:53.559 align:middle line:84%
Others say we're not
having problems at all.

00:19:53.559 --> 00:19:54.260 align:middle line:90%
So it's...

00:19:54.260 --> 00:19:55.995 align:middle line:90%
What kind of problems?

00:19:55.995 --> 00:19:59.432 align:middle line:84%
So, for example, we see the
Bundesbank saying they want

00:19:59.432 --> 00:20:05.638 align:middle line:84%
their gold back from Paris and
from New York, and, you know,

00:20:05.638 --> 00:20:08.274 align:middle line:84%
and Paris and New York
saying, "Oh well, 7 years."

00:20:08.274 --> 00:20:09.609 align:middle line:90%
Give us seven years.

00:20:09.609 --> 00:20:11.778 align:middle line:84%
[Laughter] Yeah, like give
